  "text": "Stack protection mechanisms in LLVM are implemented across multiple components that work together to detect and prevent stack buffer overflow attacks:\n\n## 1. Stack Protector Pass (llvm/lib/CodeGen/StackProtector.cpp)\nThe main LLVM pass that inserts stack protectors into functions. The `StackProtector` class is a `FunctionPass` that:\n- Detects functions requiring stack protection based on -fstack-protector flags\n- Inserts stack guard values before local variables\n- Inserts verification checks in epilogues that call `__stack_chk_fail()` if corruption is detected\n- Key function: `InsertStackProtectors()` - implements prologue/epilogue insertion logic\n- Key function: `CreateFailBB()` - creates the failure basic block with call to __stack_chk_fail\n\n## 2. Stack Protector Interface (llvm/include/llvm/CodeGen/StackProtector.h)\nDefines the public interface for stack protection:\n- `StackProtectorPass` - Modern pass interface using PassManager\n- `StackProtector` - Legacy FunctionPass interface\n- `SSPLayoutAnalysis` - Analyzes which variables trigger stack protection requirements\n- `SSPLayoutInfo` - Stores layout information for protected stack objects\n\n## 3. SafeStack Pass (llvm/lib/CodeGen/SafeStack.cpp)\nImplements the SafeStack security feature that partitions the stack into safe and unsafe regions:\n- `SafeStack` class - main implementation for separating stack allocations\n- `SafeStackLegacyPass` - legacy pass interface\n- Separates allocations that are proven safe from those that could be vulnerable\n- Unsafe allocations are moved to dynamically allocated unsafe stack managed by runtime library\n- Includes stack protector checks for unsafe stack allocations\n\n## 4. SafeStack Interface (llvm/include/llvm/CodeGen/SafeStack.h)\nDeclarates the public interface:\n- `SafeStackPass` - Modern new-PM compatible pass interface\n- Processes functions with SafeStack attribute\n\n## 5. SafeStack Layout (llvm/lib/CodeGen/SafeStackLayout.cpp/h)\nManages frame layout for safe and unsafe stacks:\n- `StackLayout` class - organizes stack objects with coloring and alignment\n- `layoutObject()` - places stack objects efficiently in memory\n- `addObject()` - registers new stack objects\n- Ensures proper separation and alignment of stack allocations\n\n## 6. Stack Check Failure Handler (libc/src/compiler/generic/__stack_chk_fail.cpp)\nRuntime implementation of the stack protection library function:\n- `__stack_chk_fail()` - called when stack corruption is detected, prints \"stack smashing detected\\n\" and aborts\n- `__stack_chk_guard` - global variable containing the random guard value (initialized to 0xa9fff01234)\n- Located in LLVM libc's compiler support library\n\n## 7. Bounds Checking Instrumentation (llvm/lib/Transforms/Instrumentation/BoundsChecking.cpp)\nProvides additional memory safety instrumentation for bounds checking:\n- `BoundsCheckingPass` - detects and instruments out-of-bounds memory access operations\n- `getBoundsCheckCond()` - determines conditions under which memory access will overflow\n- `addBoundsChecking()` - inserts checks before load/store instructions\n- Complements stack protectors with checks for heap and other memory regions\n- Header at llvm/include/llvm/Transforms/Instrumentation/BoundsChecking.h\n\nTogether, these components provide defense-in-depth against stack buffer overflow attacks: StackProtector adds canary checks, SafeStack separates unsafe allocations to protected memory, and BoundsChecking instruments memory accesses to detect violations at runtime."
}

